This question is related to http://stackoverflow.com/questions/9464280/moving-playlist-to-folder-doesnt-work. When moving a number of playlists (identified by a prefix in their names), it seems like it sometimes uses the wrong indexes and moves some (or all) other playlists to the folder instead.

This code is executed (in a `for-in`) for all playlists matching the name pattern:

```
// find out which index to use
NSUInteger playlistIndex = [[[[SPSession sharedSession] userPlaylists] playlists] indexOfObject: playlist];

// move the playlist to the target folder
BOOL success = [[[SPSession sharedSession] userPlaylists] movePlaylistOrFolderAtIndex: playlistIndex ofParent: nil toIndex: 0 ofNewParent: targetFolder error: &error];

if (success) {
    // rename playlist
    DLog(@"Success! Playlist moved to folder %@ (error: %@).", targetFolder.name, error);
    playlistMoved = YES;
} 
else {
    DLog(@"Failed to move playlist %@ with error: %@", playlist.name, error);
}
```

The problem is that in some occasions, it's not moving the right playlists. It looks like it either gets the wrong `playlistIndex` or that the index calculation being done in `-(BOOL)movePlaylistOrFolderAtIndex:ofParent:toIndex:ofNewParent:error` doesn't work properly.

Could this be an issue with how the sync (to the Spotify server) works in `cocoalibspotify` or is there something wrong with the index calc?

Encountered some strange bugs in my application and found out Bacbkone inheritance pattern seemed to be quite broken to me :

When two classes extend the same parent (siblings) seems to keep common references for parameters :

Check this simple test case :

```
    var MyParentClass = Backbone.View.extend({
        items:['foo'],
        initialize: function() {
        }
    });

    var MyFirstChildrenClass = MyParentClass.extend({
        initialize: function() {
            MyFirstChildrenClass.__super__.initialize.apply(this, arguments);
            console.warn('MyFirstChildrenClass::initalize()');
            this.items.push('bar');
        }
    });

    var MySecondChildrenClass = MyParentClass.extend({
        initialize: function() {
            MySecondChildrenClass.__super__.initialize.apply(this, arguments);
            console.warn('MySecondChildrenClass::initalize()');
            console.warn(this.items); // expecting [foo] & getting [foo,bar] !
        }
    });


    var firstInstance = new MyFirstChildrenClass();
